        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/essequibo-symbolic-election-neil-villamizar-venezuela-claim.jpg" alt="Neil Villamizar, a Navy commander who regularly appeared in uniform during his campaign, will have no power over the territory as his position is symbolic" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          Neil Villamizar, a Navy commander who regularly appeared in uniform during his campaign, will have no power over the territory as his position is symbolic. Credits: Federico Parra/AFP</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Venezuela held symbolic elections for the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-spotlight-h1-1-disputed-essequibo-region" target="_blank">disputed Essequibo region</a>, intensifying its claim against neighboring Guyana. The vote took place in a micro-district within Venezuela's Bol√≠var state, near the border. Neil Villamizar, a Navy commander from President Nicol√°s Maduro's ruling party, was elected, making him the first governor of Venezuela's newly created 24th state.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Although the Essequibo territory is administered by Guyana and had no polling stations, Villamizar called the election a step toward "full sovereignty." His role has no real power over the 160,000-square-kilometer region, but it serves as a political statement. Besides the governor, Essequibo also elected eight deputies and regional councilors.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Guyana‚Äôs President, Irfaan Ali, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-spotlight-h1-2-condemned-the-election" target="_blank">condemned the election</a> as a "threat" to his country‚Äôs territorial integrity. This border dispute has been ongoing for over a century and has gained momentum following <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-spotlight-h1-3-major-oil-discoveries" target="_blank">major oil discoveries</a> by ExxonMobil, which has raised Guyana‚Äôs global energy profile.</p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The International Court of Justice has ordered Venezuela to halt these actions. However, Maduro vowed to continue pursuing diplomatic assertions, stating that Essequibo rightfully belongs to Venezuela.</p>
        </mj-text>
