          Citizenship canceled</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: The Kuwaiti government regulates national policy and elections by stripping citizenship from people. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Kuwait recently <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-spotlight-h2-4-revoked-citizenship" target="_blank">revoked citizenship</a> for over 37,000 people, mostly women. The government asserts this move targets fraudulent naturalization and aims to "cleanse" national identity. However, it mainly impacts naturalized women, especially those who gained citizenship through marriage. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Stripping nationality of these people raises issues over due process, gender discrimination, and statelessness, especially for the already <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-spotlight-h2-5-marginalized-bidoon" target="_blank">marginalized Bidoon</a> population. This policy is part of Emir Sheikh Meshal Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah‚Äôs plan to reshape Kuwaiti identity. Analysts say that revoking nationality reduces voter numbers and increases control during periods of political gridlock.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         International human rights groups have condemned the campaign as it breaches the right to nationality. Authorities pledge the provision of certain social benefits. However, those affected still face disenfranchisement and judicial insecurity. Recently, others <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-05-2025-naturalized-for-their-achievement" target="_blank">naturalized for their achievements</a>, including pop singer Nawal Al Kuwaiti and actor Dawood Hussain, have also lost their citizenship. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
