          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
        LATAM‚Äôs copper stronghold
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: Experts recommend that the US cooperate more closely with LATAM to fix its copper dependence.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Copper is essential for the US energy, economy, and national security. However, the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-analysis-h1-6-us-mines-5" target="_blank">US mines 5%</a> of the world's supply, rendering it dependent on imports. US copper needs to double in ten years to meet rising demand from the energy transition, AI infrastructure, and electric vehicles. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Despite existing open trade agreements, most Latin American copper currently goes to China, which has secured long-term offtake agreements and dominates global copper refining. As a result, Chinese companies lead in copper refining and manufacturing, while US permission remains restricted. The US should collaborate more closely with Latin America, which is home to nearly half of the world‚Äôs reserves, making them a crucial sourcing partner.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        This suggests that the US should focus on long-term agreements and investing in mining infrastructure. The US government can also provide tools, such as concessional financing and coverage, to promote private funding in Latin American copper projects. Putting copper on the critical minerals list for the US Geological Survey would help ensure a stable copper supply in the future.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
