          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
     Why is Latin America so politically polarized?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/public-opinion-disruption-political-divide-global-change.jpg" alt="Global changes have disrupted the rules of the game regarding the formation of public opinion, leading to increased political polarization" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>Global changes have disrupted the rules of the game over the formation of public opinion, leading to increased political polarization. Credits: Latinoamerica 21</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        While most of the world appears politically polarized, Latin American elections either feature a far-left or far-right candidate. The region has long faced stark economic gaps. Wealth and power are concentrated in the hands of a few, fostering resentment and division. This inequality fuels different political views. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Currently, far-right leaders are in power in Argentina, El Salvador, and Ecuador, while a ‚Äúleft-wing‚Äù government rules Venezuela. Some support market liberalism, while others call for radical redistribution.</p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Latin America has seen authoritarian regimes, military coups, and leftist revolutions. The US <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-foundations-h1-12-backed-many-coups" target="_blank">backed many coups</a> that aligned with its ideological interests during the Cold War. These events have left lasting ideological divides and continue to shape political identities and loyalties across generations.</p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-may-25-foundations-h1-13-social-media" target="_blank">Social media</a> has recently worsened polarization. These platforms often spread misinformation and reinforce biases through algorithms. This shift has turned public discourse from constructive debate to emotional and hostile exchanges.</p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Major events, such as economic crises, political scandals, or violent protests, frequently trigger dramatic political shifts rather than incremental reform. This results in oscillation of power between ideological extremes, undermining consensus-building and long-term policy stability.</p>
       </mj-text>
